For this assignment, I utilized a Spec-Driven Development workflow to architect and deploy a "Receipt-Driven" case study modal for my Productivity Hub (Learneant App) into my existing portfolio.
 Instead of falling into the beginner's trap of prompting the AI to write the entire codebase on day one, I acted as the Project Manager while treating the AI as my Junior Developer.

I began with Phase 0 (Exploration), intentionally staying out of the weeds to have the AI propose varying design directions and content architectures. 
After evaluating the trade-offs, I converged on a "FinTech Builder" aesthetic that aligns with my major and locked in a split-layout content model highlighting both business value and technical execution.


Next, we locked the Master Spec to establish strict boundaries,
ensuring no "scope creep" would break my existing layout. 
We then executed Phase 3 in a tightly controlled sprint (Sprint 001), 
generating only the necessary HTML, CSS, and JS for the modal. 
I then ran a critique cycle, manually patching the image paths and font variables to perfectly map to my glassmorphism theme. 
Ultimately, this process taught me that an LLM's true power is unlocked not by letting it guess the final product,
but by managing it through strict constraints, clear acceptance criteria, and a locked blueprint.